      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1) is subject to a documented software quality plan including version control, regression testing, and release notes review. Internal SQA audit records confirm compliance with the plan. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects formal SQA procedures with documented evidence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Manufacturer verification benchmarks for the solver are reviewed and confirmed applicable to rotating-frame incompressible flow. Taylor–Green vortex and lid-driven cavity results reproduce published reference solutions within expected tolerances. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using the nominal, 1.5×, and 2× refined meshes. Richardson extrapolation yields a grid convergence index below 2% for the volume-averaged shear stress scalar used in the hemolysis power-law model. Discretization error is formally quantified and reported."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis tests were conducted at the five target flow-speed operating points. Blood temperature, anticoagulant protocol, and loop priming volume are documented. Deviations from clinical CPB conditions are noted and bounded."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values are compared to measured values at all five operating points. Relative errors range from 4% to 18%. Systematic over-prediction at high shear is noted and within the accepted model uncertainty envelope for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — relative hemolysis index (RH) computed from NIH at worst-case versus nominal operating point — directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1). Secondary QoIs (volume-averaged shear stress, residence time distribution) are documented and linked to the hemolysis power-law model inputs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments use the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry and operating envelope as the COU. Blood analogue fluid (glycerol–water) is used in lieu of whole blood in two of five operating points; the substitution is justified via viscosity matching and documented in the validation plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence is monitored via residual norms (all below 1×10⁻⁵) and by tracking QoI stabilisation over iterations. Time-step sensitivity for the transient sliding-mesh simulation is documented. No significant solver-introduced error is identified beyond the quantified discretization contribution."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup is peer-reviewed by a second analyst. Boundary condition inputs are cross-checked against the test rig data acquisition records. A simulation execution checklist is used and archived. No use errors were identified during review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is selected based on a literature review of blood damage models applicable to rotary blood pumps. Model form assumptions (continuum fluid, Newtonian blood analogue, steady-state approximation for impeller passage) are documented and their impact on QoI uncertainty is qualitatively bounded."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs are derived from CMM measurements of the physical pump with documented tolerances. Fluid properties (density, viscosity) are taken from ASTM-standard glycerol–water characterisation data. Inlet and outlet boundary conditions are set from time-averaged experimental flow and pressure measurements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Three pump units from the same production batch are used across the five operating-point tests to capture unit-to-unit geometric variability. Sample size justification is documented. Hematocrit and blood age are controlled and recorded for whole-blood operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not established — factor was not formally assessed.",
      "rationale": "The analysis team determined that the correspondence between CFD boundary condition inputs (inlet mass flow rate, rotational speed, outlet static pressure) and the physical test rig measurement channels is considered self-evident from the test plan documentation. A formal equivalency mapping exercise was therefore judged unnecessary and was not performed. This factor does not apply to the COU in the team's view; however, no formal scoping-out procedure was invoked and no factorStatus of 'not-applicable' was recorded. The factor consequently remains not-assessed."
    }
  ],
